= SAMPLING AND NON-SAMPLING ERROR

When you conduct research using a sample, your ultimate goal is to estimate the true
values of the entire population. However, your results will almost never be 100%
perfectly accurate. The gap between your sample's results and the true population
reality is known as Total Error.

Total error is split into two distinct categories: Sampling Error and Non-Sampling
Error.

== Sampling Error

Sampling error is the natural, unavoidable mathematical discrepancy that happens
simply because you are studying a subset of the population rather than the entire
population.

Even if your sampling design is absolutely flawless and completely random, a sample
is still just a sample. By pure chance, the people you randomly select might skew
slightly differently than the general public.

/ The Cause: Random chance. You didn't do anything wrong; it is simply a mathematical
  fact of life when taking samples.
/ Is it measurable? Yes.: This is what statistical formulas calculate. When you see a
  political poll that says "± 3% margin of error," they are explicitly measuring the
  sampling error.
/ How to reduce it: The primary way to reduce sampling error is to increase your
  sample size. The closer your sample size gets to the total population size, the
  smaller the sampling error becomes.

== Non-Sampling Error

Non-sampling errors are human, systemic, or methodological mistakes made during the
research process. These are the errors that occur outside of the mathematical bounds
of drawing a random sample.

Unlike sampling error, non-sampling error creates bias---meaning it systematically
pushes your data in the wrong direction, rather than just causing random mathematical
static.

/ The Causes: Flaws in how the study is designed, executed, or analyzed.
/ Is it measurable? Usually no.: It is incredibly difficult to mathematically
  quantify exactly how much a badly worded question skewed your results.
/ How to reduce it: You cannot fix non-sampling error by just surveying more people
  (in fact, surveying more people with a flawed survey just gives you more flawed
  data). You fix it through rigorous methodology, better survey design, and strict
  quality control.

Common Types of Non-Sampling Error:

/ Coverage Error: Your sampling frame doesn't match the population. (e.g., Conducting
  a phone survey using landline numbers, which entirely excludes young adults who
  only own cell phones).
/ Non-Response Error: The people who refuse to participate are fundamentally
  different from the people who do. (e.g., A customer satisfaction survey where only
  extremely angry or extremely happy people bother to reply).
/ Measurement/Response Error: The data collected is wrong because of how the question
  was asked or answered. (e.g., A poorly worded, confusing question, or a respondent
  lying because they are embarrassed to tell the truth).
/ Processing Error: Administrative mistakes made after the data is collected. (e.g.,
  A researcher accidentally typing "100" instead of "10" into the spreadsheet).

